In [261]:
def outlier_detect(df):
    for i in df.describe().columns:
        Q1=df.describe().at['25%',i]
        Q3=df.describe().at['75%',i]
        IQR=Q3 - Q1
        LTV=Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
        UTV=Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
        x=np.array(df[i])
        p=[]
        for j in x:
            if j < LTV or j>UTV:
               p.append(j)
        print('\n Outliers for Column : ', i, ' Outliers count ', len(p))
        print(p)

#Prepare subplots of 4 rows and 1 column
fig3, (ax31,ax32,ax33,ax34) = plt.subplots(4,1)
fig3.set_size_inches(14,28)
#Density curves to subplot for the charges distribution based on Smoker or not.
sns.kdeplot(df.loc[df["smoker"] == 1]["charges"], ax=ax31, shade=True, label='smoker')
sns.kdeplot(df.loc[df["smoker"] == 0]["charges"], ax=ax31, shade=True, label='non-smoker')
ax31.set_ylabel("Frequency", fontsize=10)
ax31.set_xlabel('Charges', fontsize=10)
ax31.set_title("Do charges of people who smoke differ significantly from the people who don't?", fontsize=14)

#Density curves to subplot for the bmi distribution, each for one of the 2 sexes
#female = 1, male = 0

ax32.set_ylabel("Frequency", fontsize=10)
ax32.set_xlabel('Bmi', fontsize=10)
ax32.set_title("Does bmi of males differ significantly from that of females?", fontsize=14)
